,"user_id":22864,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/22864/eric","reputation":7,"display_name":"Eric"},"score":-1,"is_accepted":false,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/-uS0Elf7lRBo/AAAAAAAAAAI/AAAAAAAAAE8/R5J8cBgSOg8/photo.jpg?sz=128","user_type":"registered","user_id":16299,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/16299/vance-l-albaugh","reputation":1284,"display_name":"Vance L Albaugh"},"score":0,"post_id":44737,"edited":false,"creation_date":1459361981,"comment_id":78020,"body":"Welcome to BiologySE... add some citations to the numbers you quote and it will really improve your answer; also, you could cite a reference for further reading."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1YczA.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":9943,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/9943/christiaan","reputation":26721,"display_name":"Christiaan","accept_rate":93},"score":0,"post_id":44737,"edited":false,"creation_date":1459372829,"comment_id":78041,"body":"But what determines the expression profile of a cell type?"}],"down_vote_count":2,"last_activity_date":1459361492,"creation_date":1459361492,"body":"<p>In a simplistic sense DNA can be viewed as more or less the same amongst species, but with a variability of say 0.2% between humans and chimps that might not seem like much, but it really is. A human genome is over 3 billion bases long, which means that 10s of millions of bases are different between humans and chimps and every three bases encodes an amino acid that then become one piece of a protein.<\/p>\n\n<p>As such there is a high degree of variability in the proteins expressed in a given cell. There are many homologous proteins between cells/species, which are proteins translated/transcribed from variable DNA/mRNA sequences, but ultimately serve the same function. Additonally, even though all human cells have the same genome (within the same individual), specialized control and compartmentalization of the genetic code (DNA) is why we have different organs and tissues such as the heart, skin, and lungs.<\/p>\n","answer_id":44737,"question_id":44736,"up_vote_count":1},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/70c961660418a36070b1a7c4f46df17e?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":22873,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/22873/iesha","reputation":84,"display_name":"Iesha"},"score":6,"is_accepted":true,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/210cc4a4b2f281aaffe0b26521fe1ab8?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":1590,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1590/rg255","reputation":11513,"display_name":"rg255","accept_rate":66},"score":0,"post_id":44749,"edited":false,"creation_date":1459408405,"comment_id":78051,"body":"Could you add some references &amp; supporting material to your answer please?"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/70c961660418a36070b1a7c4f46df17e?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":22873,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/22873/iesha","reputation":84,"display_name":"Iesha"},"score":0,"post_id":44749,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/210cc4a4b2f281aaffe0b26521fe1ab8?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":1590,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1590/rg255","reputation":11513,"display_name":"rg255","accept_rate":66},"edited":false,"creation_date":1459479899,"comment_id":78100,"body":"I didn&#39;t use any references per se.. everything was straight from memory from what I learned in college. I have two science degrees, one in Biomedical Sciences BS and the other in Medical Laboratory Sciences BS. If you give me a little time I could probably find some supporting data."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/210cc4a4b2f281aaffe0b26521fe1ab8?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_t