b43e11cad2fd1?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":19544,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/19544/stareagle130","reputation":23,"display_name":"stareagle130"},"score":0,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1445566508,"creation_date":1445566508,"body":"<p>I have found an acceptable answer for my question. Just post here if any interest in it. Pardon my English.<\/p>\n\n<p>Source:<\/p>\n\n<p>Nei et. al. 2010. The Neutral Theory of Molecular Evolution in the Genomic Era. Annu. Rev. Genom. Human Genet.<\/p>\n\n<p>Evolution and point mutation cause the sequence difference of the same functional protein across species. Neutral theory of molecular evolution shows that speciation level of evolution is an accumulation of molecular level of neutral evolution. In neutral evolution, the mutation only occur at a scope of point mutation in sequence in the manner that the function of the protein is retained. Overtime, speciation occurs yet the function carried out by that specific protein is still necessary and is conserved across species. Difference in protein sequence of the same functional protein is the residuals of random point mutation.<\/p>\n","answer_id":39863,"question_id":39830,"up_vote_count":0}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/39830/what-contribute-to-the-variation-of-protein-sequence-across-different-species-an","last_activity_date":1461127322,"creation_date":1445475084,"answer_count":1,"title":"What contribute to the variation of protein sequence across different species and how do they influence?","body":"<p>What contribute to the variation of protein sequence across different species (e.g. phenotype, environment, evolutionary pressure) and how do those factors contribute to the variation?<\/p>\n\n<p>I have tried to search using google + google scholar but they generally show papers discussing why and how the protein conserved across species rather than why/how the protein diverged across species. Please help me on this and references/sources are very important and highly appreciated. Thank you!<\/p>\n\n<p>An example to clarify my question. The gene CD81 is not identical among human, chimp, rat, chicken based on this identity matrix from ClustalW2. Why is CD81 not identical in all species? What factors cause the different in CD81s? How do those factors cause that (e.g. evolutionary pressure)?\n#\n#<\/p>\n\n<h1>Percent Identity  Matrix - created by Clustal2.1<\/h1>\n\n<p>#\n#<\/p>\n\n<pre><code> 1: sp|P60033|CD81_HUMAN    100.00  100.00   93.22   82.55\n 2: sp|P60034|CD81_PANTR    100.00  100.00   93.22   82.55\n 3: sp|Q62745|CD81_RAT       93.22   93.22  100.00   82.55\n 4: tr|F1NW06|F1NW06_CHICK   82.55   82.55   82.55  100.00\n<\/code><\/pre>\n","question_id":39830,"tags":["evolution","phylogenetics"],"score":2,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":false,"view_count":43,"up_vote_count":2,"last_edit_date":1445483899},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/f9bda794bc71267206358bf04ea0a179?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":3677,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3677/mscha","reputation":124,"display_name":"mscha"},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/de2c4fd753821f85c74d886aa17410de?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":107,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/107/kmm","reputation":8486,"display_name":"kmm"},"score":4,"post_id":8560,"edited":false,"creation_date":1369747128,"comment_id":10926,"body":"Is there any reason to believe that it is a real species at all?"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1MUb2.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":1306,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1306/terdon","reputation":9339,"display_name":"terdon","accept_rate":73},"score":1,"post_id":8560,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/de2c4fd753821f85c74d886aa17410de?s=128&d=identic