0,"display_name":"Hav0k"},"score":0,"post_id":45391,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/2bdd00456ffc689017c8405d93a14a3b?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"unregistered","user_id":23323,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/23323/sean","reputation":1,"display_name":"Sean"},"edited":false,"creation_date":1461095944,"comment_id":79469,"body":"To partition the R&#178; you can start out with a single-predictor model and add predictors while keeping track of the increment in R&#178;. However, since your predictors are not completely uncorrelated, the partial R&#178; will differ depending on the order of variable entrance. Another way to compare effect sizes would be to standardize each variable (i.e. compute z-values) and look at the estimated coefficients."}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1461090026,"creation_date":1461090026,"body":"<p>First of all, species richness is most likely the <em>dependent<\/em> variable (the one you want to explain), while distance to the source pool and pH are the <em>independent<\/em> variables (the ones you assume to have an effect on species richness).<\/p>\n\n<p>The problem you are describing is termed <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Multicollinearity\" rel=\"nofollow\">multicollinearity<\/a> and a common problem in regression analyses. The good news is that it does not affect the prediction of your model as a whole. The bad news is that the estimates for you individual predictors become increasingly erratic the higher their correlation is. You can estimate the severeness of multicollinearity in your model with the Variance inflation factor (VIF). Wikipedia explains nicely how to interpret the VIF:<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>The square root of the variance inflation factor tells you how much larger the standard error is, compared with what it would be if that variable were uncorrelated with the other predictor variables in the model.<\/p>\n  \n  <p>Example\n  If the variance inflation factor of a predictor variable were 5.27 (√5.27 = 2.3) this means that the standard error for the coefficient of that predictor variable is 2.3 times as large as it would be if that predictor variable were uncorrelated with the other predictor variables.<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>You should calculate the VIF for your model. Many sources state that a VIF &lt; 10 is still acceptable, but since <a href=\"http://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s11135-006-9018-6\" rel=\"nofollow\">there is no rule of thumb<\/a>, I suggest to do some further reading on the topic if you get some critical value (just google \"dealing with collinearity\" and you'll find tons of material).<\/p>\n","answer_id":45391,"question_id":45386,"up_vote_count":0}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/45386/distance-to-source-populations-and-or-environmental-gradients","last_activity_date":1461090026,"creation_date":1461085676,"answer_count":1,"title":"Distance to source populations and/or environmental gradients?","body":"<p>How do you disentangle the effects of distance to source populations and environmental gradients when the environmental gradient occurs in the same direction as the source population? <\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/suvU0.png\" rel=\"nofollow\"><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/suvU0.png\" alt=\"http://i.imgur.com/iWDfblq.png\"><\/a><\/p>\n\n<p>For example, if I have a regression model with species richness as the independent variable and distance to source population and pH as significant dependent variables, how do I know which is the driving factor?<\/p>\n","question_id":45386,"tags":["community-ecology","landscape-ecology"],"score":0,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":false,"view_count":22,"up_vote_count":0,"last_edit_date":1461085856},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/BI7vp.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":17400,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/17400/gwenn","reputation":582,"display_name"