ess function. One of the features of the fitness function is that I think there should be exponential payoffs in terms of reproductive success near the solution $\\vec{q}$. Further, I think there are probably other very important environmental factors that might lead to such convergence. An arboreal jumping spider of similar size that shares the same environment as leaf-cutter ants is a good example."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/pFhME.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":19277,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/19277/iayork","reputation":1582,"display_name":"iayork"},"score":0,"post_id":45338,"edited":false,"creation_date":1461066832,"comment_id":79402,"body":"@Aidan Rocke How does a cube become 1% more like a sphere? It rounds off the corners a little bit, obviously.   How is this a difficult concept? The same applies with mimicry.  The whole point about evolution is that tiny advantages, compounded, become large advantages."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/2zmAC.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":9573,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/9573/aidan-rocke","reputation":360,"display_name":"Aidan Rocke","accept_rate":75},"score":0,"post_id":45338,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/pFhME.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":19277,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/19277/iayork","reputation":1582,"display_name":"iayork"},"edited":false,"creation_date":1461069752,"comment_id":79409,"body":"@iayork Your argument is actually false. Show me the computation that determines that a cube is &#39;1%&#39; more spherical when its corners are rounded. Now, in general how are you supposed to do such a calculation of &#39;percentage similarity&#39; assuming that some of the variables are independent from each other and some are strongly correlated."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/pFhME.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"r