. Elongation, starting with stearate (18:0), is performed mainly in the ER by several membrane-bound enzymes.<\/strong> The enzymatic steps involved in the elongation process are principally the same as those carried out by FAS, but the four principal successive steps of the elongation are performed by individual proteins, which may be physically associated.<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fatty_acid_synthesis#Straight-chain_fatty_acids\" rel=\"nofollow\">Source<\/a><\/p>\n\n<p>Another article from <a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2764369/#S5title\" rel=\"nofollow\">NCBI<\/a> states:<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>Primers for several mouse, rat, and human elongases have been reported elsewhere.<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>...and cites <a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/16790840\" rel=\"nofollow\">here<\/a> for this.<\/p>\n\n<p>So, as Wikipedia and NCBI say, animals do have elongase, by which fatty acids longer than 16 carbons can be synthesized.<\/p>\n","answer_id":45361,"question_id":20934,"up_vote_count":0}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/20934/synthesis-of-fatty-acids-longer-than-16-carbons","last_activity_date":1461062995,"creation_date":1409593809,"answer_count":1,"title":"Synthesis of Fatty Acids Longer than 16 Carbons","body":"<p>I understand that the human body when performing Fatty Acid Synthesis can synthesize only until C16 (palmitate). However the ER has desaturases and elongases. I know that desaturases are used to add double bonds, but do humans have elongases to add even more Carbons to a double bond? If so, then this would mean that the human body can synthesize fats longer than C16? <\/p>\n\n<p>Lets take a hypothetical case and say that humans have both desaturases and elongases. Would it be feasible to add double bonds to palmitate via desaturases, then add more carbons to the chain via elongases and then add more double bonds via desaturases? This way, the resulting fatty acid will have an increased length and more unsaturated character (i.e. more double bonds than the prescribed 4 that humans can add at positions 4, 5, 6, and 9)?<\/p>\n","question_id":20934,"tags":["biochemistry","lipids","fat-metabolism"],"score":4,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":false,"view_count":81,"up_vote_count":4,"last_edit_date":1448564627},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/265a636403a666dfd073e77e24ef8651?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":21363,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/21363/biology-nerd","reputation":4,"display_name":"Biology nerd"},"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/45354/what-is-the-optimum-ph-of-isospora-suis","last_activity_date":1461061151,"creation_date":1461053652,"answer_count":0,"title":"What is the optimum pH of Isospora suis?","body":"<p>What pH range does the <em>Isospora suis<\/em> parasite thrive most? If you can give me any information, please give me a paper about this as well. <\/p>\n","question_id":45354,"tags":["reference-request","parasitology"],"score":0,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":false,"view_count":8,"up_vote_count":0,"last_edit_date":1461061151},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/be56c31dfd035cad14d4e9ae17252ab2?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":22087,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/22087/rocc","reputation":142,"display_name":"rocc"},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/kIqWF.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":19099,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/19099/another-homo-sapien","reputation":1004,"display_name":"another 'Homo sapien'"},"score":0,"post_id":45040,"edited":false,"creation_date":1460542828,"comment_id":79000,"body":"See <a href=\"http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0167488908004151\" rel=\"nofollow\">sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0167488908004151<\/a>"}],"link":"http://biology.st