wo or more forms of the same DNA sequence existing; which one you have depends mostly on which one you inherited from your parents. There are also polymorphisms that are created by imprecise DNA duplication during meiosis. Array-length polymorphisms can be explained by the latter.<\/p>\n\n<p>As the DNA in centromeres is highly repetetive, it can happen that during replication, the number of repeats is decreased or increased. This leads to many different copy numbers in different individuals. Therefore, your answer cannot be answered with a specific number.<\/p>\n","answer_id":44398,"question_id":44396,"up_vote_count":0},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/b7c3a661d4f9ffe4bf96926b4050779c?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":23303,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/23303/young","reputation":59,"display_name":"Young"},"score":1,"is_accepted":false,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/7a12f428f1b8b3752a20918f436baf7f?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":17001,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/17001/blindkungfumaster","reputation":170,"display_name":"BlindKungFuMaster"},"score":0,"post_id":45346,"edited":false,"creation_date":1461051330,"comment_id":79372,"body":"My question is about the length in base pairs. My understanding is that you can sequence centromeres, you just cannot assemble them. But the sequencing reads might be enough to give an estimate of the total base count."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/b7c3a661d4f9ffe4bf96926b4050779c?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":23303,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/23303/young","reputation":59,"display_name":"Young"},"score":0,"post_id":45346,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/7a12f428f1b8b3752a20918f436baf7f?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":17001,"link":"http