 human chromosomes. <\/p>\n\n<p>The best I could come up with so far has been: <a href=\"http://www.pnas.org/content/86/23/9394.full.pdf\" rel=\"nofollow\">The length of individual centromeric arrays was found to range from an average of 680 kilobases for the Y chromosome to 3000 kb for chromosome 11.<\/a><\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3966626/\" rel=\"nofollow\">Here they say<\/a> that \"Human centromeres are located at repetitive alpha satellite DNA arrays that compose approximately 5% of the genome.\" Which unfortunately is not the same as saying the centromeres compose 5% of the genome. (Or maybe it is? Biologists to the rescue!)<\/p>\n\n<p>Ideally an answer would contain the length of the centromere in each chromosome, but a precise percentage for the whole human genome would be good enough. <\/p>\n","question_id":44396,"tags":["dna","chromosome"],"score":2,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":39,"up_vote_count":2,"last_edit_date":1458310237},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/oOxxZ.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":13297,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/13297/axsvl77","reputation":119,"display_name":"axsvl77"},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/oOxxZ.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":13297,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/13297/axsvl77","reputation":119,"display_name":"axsvl77"},"score":0,"post_id":28232,"edited":false,"creation_date":1422811488,"comment_id":46178,"body":"Doesn&#39;t have to be in English either"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/5c0cf46c3426ba3b0eebe6163d1aa130?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":6003,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/6003/dan-horvat","reputation":304,"display_name":"Dan Horvat"},"score":0,"post_id":28232,"edited":false,"creation_date":1433724807,"comment_id":56547,"body":"David Attenborough I stay away from. 