,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4108/remi-b","reputation":22909,"display_name":"Remi.b","accept_rate":88},"score":1,"post_id":42280,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/61c96b63684953323e2d0b8b1b329da9?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":10184,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/10184/user1205901","reputation":219,"display_name":"user1205901","accept_rate":60},"edited":false,"creation_date":1452961060,"comment_id":72816,"body":"@user1205901 Exactly. As you said if $h_B=0$, then none of the phenotypic variance is due to genetic variance. In other words, there exists no gene which is currently polymorphic and which polymorphism affect phenotypic variance in the population in this environment. I added two small paragraphs to try to troubleshoot potential misconceptions about heritability."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/61c96b63684953323e2d0b8b1b329da9?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":10184,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/10184/user1205901","reputation":219,"display_name":"user1205901","accept_rate":60},"score":0,"post_id":42280,"edited":false,"creation_date":1452996716,"comment_id":72862,"body":"So, if $h_B=0$ then there is no point looking for polymorphic genes that affect the trait. Turkheimer says that heritability coefficients are &quot;not...a useful indicator of how successful gene-finding efforts are likely to be&quot;. However, isn&#39;t it the case that the heritability statistic is somewhat useful in telling us whether to devote efforts to gene-finding? If $h_B=0$ we are definitely wasting our time on gene-finding efforts, if $h_B=0.00001$ we are most likely wasting our time, whereas if $h_B=0.9999$ gene-finding efforts are more likely to be successful?"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1sIMq.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":4108,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4108/remi-b","reputation":22909,"display_name":"Remi.b","accept_rate":88},"score":1,"post_id":42280,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/61c96b63684953323e2d0b8b1b329da9?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":10184,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/10184/user1205901","reputation":219,"display_name":"user1205901","accept_rate":60},"edited":false,"creation_date":1452997607,"comment_id":72864,"body":"If $h_B=0$, then you are definitely wasting your time in trying to find genes which variance in the population affect the phenotypic variance in the population because there are none. But if $h_B≠0$, then there are such genes (or other non-coding sequence). All else being equal (typically the number of genes that affect the trait (which are called QTL btw)), the higher the heritability the smaller the sample size you will need to find the QTL."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1sIMq.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":4108,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4108/remi-b","reputation":22909,"display_name":"Remi.b","accept_rate":88},"score":1,"post_id":42280,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/61c96b63684953323e2d0b8b1b329da9?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":10184,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/10184/user1205901","reputation":219,"display_name":"user1205901","accept_rate":60},"edited":false,"creation_date":1452997610,"comment_id":72865,"body":"Note again that when $h_B=0$, you might still be interesting in the genes that are involved into the building of the trait even if these genes are not polymorphic."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/210cc4a4b2f281aaffe0b26521fe1ab8?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":1590,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1590/rg255","reputation":11513,"display_name":"rg255","accept_rate":66},"score":0,"post_