<\/blockquote>\n\n<p><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/UsThc.jpg\" alt=\"enter image description here\">\nFIGURE 1: <strong>Overall alignment performance for each of the MSA programs tested.<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<p>(A) Overall Accuracy <\/p>\n\n<p>(B) Total run time for constructing all alignments (a log10 scale is used for display purposes).<\/p>\n\n<p>doi:10.1371/journal.pone.0018093.g003<\/p>\n\n<h2>Compared Tools<\/h2>\n\n<p><img src=\"http://www.plosone.org/article/fetchObject.action?uri=info:doi/10.1371/journal.pone.0018093.t001&amp;representation=PNG_L\" alt=\"\"><\/p>\n\n<p>Source and Photo Credits: <\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://www.plosone.org/article/info%3Adoi%2F10.1371%2Fjournal.pone.0018093#pone-0018093-g003\" rel=\"nofollow\">A Comprehensive Benchmark Study of Multiple Sequence Alignment Methods: Current Challenges and Future Perspectives<\/a> <\/p>\n\n<p>PS: This is from an old paper of 2011. If you want the new statistics you can always test on your own, by the process described in the source paper.<\/p>\n","answer_id":20085,"question_id":20075,"up_vote_count":4},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/2529c7a350c7665df3acdcd073f75167?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":13093,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/13093/steve-bond","reputation":324,"display_name":"Steve Bond"},"score":1,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1421677332,"creation_date":1421677332,"body":"<p>The PRANK and PAGAN algorithms have both come out of the Loytynoja lab in Finnland, and are stirring up the pot a bit. They use inferred phylogenetic relationships as a parameter, and tend to yield a much more 'gappy' alignment, supposedly due to more accurate handling of indels. For easy alignments the method doesn't matter so much, but if the sequences are highly divergent it might be worth while checking out <a href=\"http://wasabiapp.org/software/pagan/\" rel=\"nofollow\">PAGAN<\/a> and <a href=\"http://wasabiapp.org/software/prank/\" rel=\"nofollow\">PRANK<\/a>.<\/p>\n","answer_id":27832,"question_id":20075,"up_vote_count":1},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/ay2bH.gif?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":22057,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/22057/david","reputation":1825,"display_name":"David"},"score":0,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1460977480,"creation_date":1460977480,"body":"<p>Clustal has reinvented itself as <a href=\"http://msb.embopress.org/content/7/1/539\" rel=\"nofollow\">Clustal Omega<\/a> using Hidden Markov Models, and is particularly suited to the alignment of very many sequences. <\/p>\n","answer_id":45327,"question_id":20075,"up_vote_count":0}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/20075/what-is-the-state-of-the-art-algorithm-for-multiple-sequence-alignment","last_activity_date":1460977480,"creation_date":1406707810,"answer_count":3,"title":"What is the state-of-the-art algorithm for multiple sequence alignment?","body":"<p>Which algorithm or algorithms are considered the <em>standard<\/em> or <em>state-of-the-art<\/em> for <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Multiple_sequence_alignment\">multiple sequence alignment<\/a>?<\/p>\n\n<p>How big is the need for better algorithms? How many sequences need to be alignment in a typical test? I am trying to understand how important problem this is in bioinformatics.<\/p>\n","question_id":20075,"tags":["bioinformatics","sequence-analysis","sequence-alignment"],"score":4,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":253,"up_vote_count":4},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/f36c925c04e09db23e613a91970f420c?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":23223,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/23223/kodlu","reputation":103,"display_name":"kodlu"},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/f437d9a11deebd214089822c26197f35?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":3553,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3553/james","reputation":4533,"display_name":"James","accept_rate":83},"score":1,"post_id":45272,"edited":false,"creation_date":1460861991,"comment_id":79223,"body":"This question is unclear. What do you mean by A,B, C and D? Are these residues, or points in a list. I think you should expand on your toy sequences.Assuming you can&#39;t post your actual sequences, perhaps use another real peptide and make up similar constraints to the ones in your own problem (although I still don&#39;t understand what your constraints are)."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/2550aa98332616362fa07d023da45d40?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":28,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/28/gergana-vandova","reputation":5081,"display_name":"Gergana Vandova","accept_rate":35},"score":1,"post_id":45272,"edited":false,"creation_date":1460869807,"comment_id":79224,"body":"I also don&#39;t understand your constraints. Also, why do you need constraints? Usually when you do MSA, you don&#39;t pose any constraints since you presumably don&#39;t know how the query sequences can be aligned. Also, I bet that if you include sequence &quot;p&quot; in your MSA, the alignment will be different and will include your constraints."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/f36c925c04e09db23e613a91970f420c?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":23223,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/23223/kodlu","reputation":103,"display_name":"kodlu"},"score":0,"post_id":45272,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/f437d9a11deebd214089822c26197f35?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":3553,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3553/james","reputation":4533,"display_name":"James","accept_rate":83},"edited":false,"creation_date":1460930674,"comment_id":79259,"body":"@James, 