010.pdf<\/a>). There is no concrete literature about the ratio of dry weight to total weight, but it is thought to be around 50-70%. Again these are avg. estimates."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/ef567acea1fa50e6645a1c5b3618f12f?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":22560,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/22560/grb","reputation":51,"display_name":"Grb"},"score":0,"post_id":44360,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/74bcb23ef9e019ed7fe407e8bfa47f5c?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":15695,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/15695/roland","reputation":2431,"display_name":"Roland"},"edited":false,"creation_date":1460942617,"comment_id":79267,"body":"Thanks for pointing out the calculation mistake @Roland .Of course for an accurate analysis you may need direct density measurement data, and also in that sense you will only get an average density of the cell as cells are highly heterogeneous. What I mentioned along with the specific references are some of the evidences of what have been done so far."}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1460942434,"creation_date":1458181135,"body":"<p>The most common opinion about this is a bacterium weighs about 10^-12 g. Here is a link with different results found using different techniques: <a href=\"http://hypertextbook.com/facts/2003/LouisSiu.shtml\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://hypertextbook.com/facts/2003/LouisSiu.shtml<\/a><\/p>\n\n<p>This link also has useful relevant numbers, good to keep alongside: <a href=\"http://kirschner.med.harvard.edu/files/bionumbers/fundamentalBioNumbersHandout.pdf\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://kirschner.med.harvard.edu/files/bionumbers/fundamentalBioNumbersHandout.pdf<\/a><\/p>\n\n<p>Assuming a bacterial cell has a volume of 1 um^3 (10^-18 m^3; 0.001 pL) and 1 pg in mass, the density should be around 10^3 pg/pL. Similarly you can find out for other cell types.<\/p>\n\n<p>Cheers!<\/p>\n","answer_id":44360,"question_id":44357,"up_vote_count":0,"last_edit_date":1460942434},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/74bcb23ef9e019ed7fe407e8bfa47f5c?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":15695,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/15695/roland","reputation":2431,"display_name":"Roland"},"score":0,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1460796530,"creation_date":1460796530,"body":"<p>Density of a variety of cell types is rather well known. It can been measured directly by examining buoyancy (tendency to float) in liquids of known density, and also by <a href=\"http://manalis-lab.mit.edu/resonators.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">microfluidic methods<\/a>. But the results depend on the <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Plasma_osmolality\" rel=\"nofollow\">osmolality<\/a> of the solution in which the cells are kept, since cells tend to \"swell\" (take up water) in low osmolality (hypotonic) medium.<\/p>\n\n<p>Using a microfluidic technique, <a href=\"http://manalis-lab.mit.edu/publications/godin_APL_2007.pdf\" rel=\"nofollow\">this paper<\/a> reports a density of 1160 $\\pm$ 1 pg/pL for <em>E.coli<\/em> at 290 mOsm, and 1139 $\\pm$ 3 pg/pL for red blood cells. At comparable osmolality and using a gradient centrifugation method, <a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC176578/\" rel=\"nofollow\">this paper<\/a> gives a density of 1095 pg/pL for <em>E.Coli<\/em>. So the results clearly differ a bit depending on experimental conditions (possibly the medium composition was different). For budding yeast, <a href=\"http://manalis-lab.mit.edu/publications/bryan_PNAS_2009.pdf\" rel=\"nofollow\">this paper<\/a> estimates a density of 1103 $\\pm$ 3 pg/pL, compared to 1113 pg/pL by gradient centrifugation.<\/p>\n\n<p>In all cases, cells are heavier than pure water (1000 pg/pL), and larger eukaryotic cells seem to be slightly more dense. As macromolecules are more dense than water, this would suggest that eukaryotes have lower water content.<\/p>\n","answer_id":45280,"question_id":44357,"up_vote_count":0}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/44357/cellular-specific-mass-in-grams-dry-weight-per-pico-liter","last_activity_date":1460942434,"creation_date":1458165349,"answer_count":2,"title":"Cellular specific mass (in grams-dry-weight per pico liter)?","body":"<p>What is the cellular specific mass, in units of pgDW (pico-gram dry-weight) per pL (pico liter)?<\/p>\n\n<p>I suspect there is some variability between cell types, but this variability must be limited. Perhaps bacteria and mammalian cells are different, but the number shouldn't change much among bacteria. This is just intuition, I could be wrong.<\/p>\n\n<p>So, what is the cellular specific mass, for different cell types (assuming there is limited variability, so this is not an infinite table)?<\/p>\n","question_id":44357,"tags":["cell-biology"],"score":1,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":false,"view_count":42,"up_vote_count":1},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/775e4b5b5ba3b164d689f54cbdff0ae0?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":23272,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/23272/goro","reputation":101,"display_name":"goro"},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/74bcb23ef9e019ed7fe407e8bfa47f5c?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":15695,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/15695/roland","reputation":2431,"display_name":"Roland"},"score":0,"post_id":45315,"edited":false,"creation_date":1460955853,"comment_id":79275,"body":"Aspartate is not a product of the urea cycle nor gluconeogenesis; it is a substrate for both processes. Also, the question seems broad and open-ended. Aspartate is a central metabolite and a large number of factors could affect its metabolism / concentration. It sounds like you&#39;re asking for a literature review ..